WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.998
Impressions on Google Glass

00:00:03.498 --> 00:00:06.374
Published on September 15, 2013.

00:00:07.374 --> 00:00:11.610
I had a chance to play around with Google Glass Explorer Edition via my employer .

00:00:12.110 --> 00:00:20.661
I was able to successfully hook it up to my personal Google account, contrary to stuff I’ve read about the Explorer program not allowing loans, etc.

00:00:21.161 --> 00:00:26.115
If there’s a specific policy behind that, it doesn’t seem to be enforced on a technical level.

00:00:27.115 --> 00:00:31.430
Anyway, I figured I should write down some of my initial impressions on the thing.

00:00:31.930 --> 00:00:39.842
It’s always interesting to look back and see how well I did in my predictions, like when I thought Twitter was just for narcissists (not sure I was wrong on that one).

00:00:40.842 --> 00:00:48.834
The two strong feelings I have from Google Glass are that I wish it was less visible (to others) and I think it will greatly improve on video and photo sharing.

00:00:49.834 --> 00:00:58.944
While I understand that technology can work as a fashion accessory (see anyone who owns an iPhone), I also feel like it shouldn’t burden the user with its outward appearance.

00:00:59.444 --> 00:01:07.196
Everyone writes about how Google Glass will create some kind of panopticon state, but the one wearing them is really the one who feels watched.

00:01:07.696 --> 00:01:14.089
I once tried walking to get my mail while wearing the gadget, and felt super awkward as I said hi to a neighbor.

00:01:14.589 --> 00:01:21.701
The awkwardness could have also had something to do with the fact that I have to wear the Google Glass over my normal glasses, which looks super dumb.

00:01:22.701 --> 00:01:29.574
On a positive note, I think the ability to take first person videos is going to be the killer feature of Google Glass, if one ends up existing.

00:01:30.074 --> 00:01:40.863
I took a few videos of myself making dinner, which aren’t really that interesting now, but I can see a sort of lifestream genre bubble up from taking short videos of doing really mundane stuff day to day.

