00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:51.712
As far as developing for the Glass, I found that the Google Mirror API is a bit lacking if you don’t already have some existing app you’d like to integrate.

00:01:52.212 --> 00:01:57.886
It’s basically glorified push notifications with a few extra location features built in.

00:01:58.386 --> 00:02:07.177
As an Android noob, I haven’t really pushed anything interesting to the Glass device yet in terms of native apps (just the Hello World one and a few samples).

00:02:07.677 --> 00:02:13.590
I’d wait for the official GDK to start developing in earnest, and maybe in the meantime, learn Android.

00:02:14.590 --> 00:02:17.787
I had some mixed experiences with the Glass, overall.

00:02:18.287 --> 00:02:25.000
While the technology is neat, I feel there are many social hurdles that the device must pass before the thing can take off.

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:28.536
Remember those Bluetooth headsets that you can wear on your ear?

00:02:29.036 --> 00:02:34.230
Google Glass is basically twice as useful, yet also twice as awkward.

00:02:34.730 --> 00:02:41.923
I think that a lot of the awkwardness will go away once sub-vocal microphone technology advances to the consumer level (think Metal Gear Solid).

00:02:42.423 --> 00:02:47.777
Then all Glass will need is a makeover to disguise the camera and screen into a normal set of glasses.

00:02:48.277 --> 00:02:53.151
Once the technology becomes outwardly invisible, the technology will be able to speak for itself.

